^B@2Simple (non forcing) Stayman:

Stayman is THE convention used to find a 4-4 Major fit when Partner opened the bidding with 1NT
(Here will be referred to the strong 1NT : 15-17 )

More and more, 1NT (and 2NT) are opened with 5 card majors and especially over 2NT "puppet Stayman" 
has gained in popularity.
Here I will adress "basic Stayman"
Regardless if you open 1NT with a 5-card major, Stayman is still a very usefull convention.

1NT        2@c = the Stayman convention

It's an artificial bid with a clear question: Partner, do you have a 4-card Major?

Do you use Stayman with less than invitational hands? 
NO, you simply pass as there are no game perspectives.
(on a very rare occasion you might bid "garbage Stayman", more later)

To be invitational or game forcing (GF) you will need |cp|6|at|^*B8+ HCP^*N|cp|2|at|, you can do the math:
If partner opened 1NT with 15 HCP: You don't want to be in game when you have 8 (15+8=23) 
But if partner opened with 17 (17+8=25) you have a fair chance for game, 
Especially when you have a hand better than a 4-3-3-3 distribution.
 
8 HCP and 4-3-3-3 might be a perfect pass,
But 8+ and a better distribution AND a 4-card Major go Stayman :)|
