Responding to partner's 2@c Stayman:

Life for Opener is easy, as there are only 3 responses available:

- 2@h = yes, I have a 4+ card @h (and I might hold a 4-card @s) 
- 2@s = yes, I have a 4+ card @s (and I certainly do not have a 4-card @h)
- 2@d = no partner, I don't have a 4-card Major

If opener has 2 4-cards in the Majors, he will bid them "up the line" ie @h's first. 
(Showing spades denies hearts!)
"strength" is not part of the answer! Lacking a Major, you do NOT bid 2NT when maximum!   2@d is your answer
The reason to bid them up the line will become clear shorthly

And what if you as Responder to 1NT hold 4-4 in the Majors, or even 5-4 or 6-4?
Stayman is still your bid!

With the following example hands you should get the idea

Your rebids after partner's response to your Stayman will vary depending on your values: 
Are you invitational or GF and 4-4 or 5-4 (or even 6-4)?

Let's look at some hands where Stayman is the bid, and opener's responses
and how to take it from there....

