^b{ 2@d and 2@h, the basic Jacoby transfer bids }|fp|1|ht|d|cs|3|at|^B@2
Though invented by the Swedish player Olle Willner (!) years before O.Jacoby introduced them to N.American players,
they are now widely known as "Jacoby transfers"

What is the idea behind a transfer (2@d or 2@h transferring to 2@h/2@s respectively) after a 1NT opening by P?
Among others, that the stronger hand (partner's, who opened 1NT) will be the delarer
(he will be the one bidding the "real" suit). His hand with the HCP won't end up laying on the table as dummy,
which would be a huge advantage for the defenders!
In other words, it protects partner's, usually stronger hand.
Also, the opening lead will not go through partner's strength, but rather "into" partner's strength.
The 1NT bidder frequently holds combinations of honors (called tenaces) that are worth more tricks if the defenders lead "into" them rather than "through" them. 
For example, if you hold the @h AQ, you'ld like your left-hand opponent to lead a heart for you, but not your RHO.

Playing Jacoby transfers opens a whole new set of bidding options.
They can be used for weak hands, invitational hands, GF hands and slam hands.

They can be used after 1NT and 2NT openers, as well as after  
2@c    2@d
2NT/3NT rebids (which would still show balanced hands, just outside the 15-17 or 20-21 range)  


This is how it basically works:
1NT   ^d2@d = transfer to @h
2@h
or
1NT   ^d2@h = transfer to @s
2@s|
